<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-12T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-12T12:00:00-05:00" n="227" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d227">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">862.248/112: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-12T18:00:00+01:00">March 12, 1935—6
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 12—2:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>46. Interview of Goering<note n="28" xml:id="d227fn28">Hermann
                                    Goering, German Minister for Aviation.</note> with <hi rend="italic">Daily Mail</hi> representative chosen as means to
                                announce air program. Reliable sources do not believe its
                                announcement is directly retaliatory against British White
                                    Paper<note n="29" xml:id="d227fn29">See British Cmd. 4827: <hi rend="italic">Statement Relating to Defense Issued in
                                        Connexion With the House of Commons Debate on March 11,
                                        1985</hi>. This command paper was dated March 1, 1935, and
                                    apparently was released on March 4 in anticipation of the
                                    scheduled debate on imperial defense.</note> but simply publicly
                                indicates completion of a military plan regardless of treaty
                                stipulations.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dodd</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>